  "prompt": "Why does Greece have a debt crisis, but Japan doesn't?",
  "response": "The debt situations of Greece and Japan differ significantly due to several key factors:\n\nGreece's Debt Crisis:\n1. Smaller, less diversified economy\n2. Weak tax collection system\n3. High government spending relative to economic output\n4. Limited ability to print its own currency (part of Eurozone)\n5. Structural economic weaknesses\n6. Limited industrial base\n7. Reliance on tourism and services\n8. Borrowed at high interest rates\n\nJapan's Sustainable Debt:\n1. Large, diversified, advanced economy\n2. High domestic savings rate\n3. Most debt held internally by Japanese institutions/citizens\n4. Independent monetary policy\n5. Can print its own currency (yen)\n6. Strong industrial and technological sectors\n7. Consistent trade surpluses\n8. Low interest rates on government bonds\n9. High technological productivity\n10. Stable political system\n\nThe fundamental difference is that Japan has economic fundamentals and financial mechanisms that allow it to manage its high debt, while Greece lacks those stabilizing factors. Japan's debt, though high, is considered manageable due to its economic strength and internal debt ownership, whereas Greece's debt became unsustainable due to structural economic weaknesses.",
